    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm working on a research paper and i keep getting told my writing is too passive. can u help me figure out how to spot it and fix it? like maybe with an example?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A passive voice occurs when the subject of the sentence receives the action, and it can be marked by the use of the verb \"to be\" (e.g. \"was,\" \"is,\" \"are\") or a linking verb (e.g. \"been\"). To spot it, look for sentences that start with a form of \"to be\" or use a linking verb. Here's an example: \"The ball was thrown by John.\" Replacing this sentence with an active voice version would make it more engaging: \"John threw the ball.\" \n\nFor further improvement, try rephrasing sentences to put the subject in the action, like this: \"The new policy is being implemented\" becomes \"The company will implement the new policy.\"",
      "source": "target",
