    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that makes sense. i see a lot of my sentences are like that, where it feels like the thing being acted on is being placed at the front and the person doing the thing is being hidden or shoved to the end. is there a trick to how to actually find them in a long paragraph?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "One trick to identify passive voice is to look for sentences that end with a verb such as \"was found,\" \"is being done,\" or \"were given.\" By identifying these patterns, you can pinpoint sentences that are in passive voice, and rephrase them to active voice.\n\nYou can also try highlighting sentences in your paragraph as you go through it, focusing on places where the verb is being paired with \"was,\" \"is,\" or \"were.\" When you notice these patterns, rephrase the sentence by reversing the actions to put the person or entity doing the action at the front of the sentence.\n\nAnother approach is to write \"active verbs only\": take the main action and replace it with an alternative verb that maintains the same meaning, like adding the pronoun \"I\" or \"she\" at the beginning of a sentence. This will help you identify and rephrase passive sentences more easily.",
      "source": "target",
